body:
Time

Idea… not for me because my knowledge of the finer details of the series is far too weak…

-

Jaime never went back for Brienne and she was killed by the bear. Him making the decision to rescue her was an absolute turning point of him becoming a better person (though he still fumbled here and there) so how would things be different for not only Jaime but everyone? What effect would it have on the war(s)?

-

Now imagine Bran/Three Eyed Raven is aware of what would have happened IF she lived and crucial events connected to the survival rely on her still being around…so he wargs into a soldier during that stop and convinces Jaime to understand going back to save her is dire. But it has to be Jaime’s decision (the whole moral turning point) And then everything returns to where it should be…

-

Now that would be a cool story. If already done link it my way!

summary:
so, uhhhh...
What's the deal with religion in the New Six Kingdoms?
Cersei blew up the Sept of Baelor and presumably removed...
body:
so, uhhhh…

What’s the deal with religion in the New Six Kingdoms?

Cersei blew up the Sept of Baelor and presumably removed several high ranking members of the church in the process, but the organization as a whole still has to exist in some capacity. Every other city in Westeros has a Sept, no? Surely they are in the process of reorganizing and at least attempting to reclaim some of their institutional power.

How are they going to feel about a King who almost certainly does not subscribe to their beliefs? Not just because Bran was raised in the North, because he did have Catelyn there to teach him about the Seven. But more because Bran himself is basically an Old God made flesh.

Something tells me that when Bran has his coronation, no Septons will be present, and no oaths involving the Seven will be sworn.

Something tells me the Faith of the Seven won’t be too happy about that.

Something tells me that they might even try to do something about it.

And something tells me that they will fail, because unlike the Seven-in-One, Bran is very real and very powerful.

(no seriously, I’m pretty sure the Faith of the Seven is a sham, because of all the Gods invoked in the series– the Many-faced God, the Lord of Light, the Old Gods of the Forest, the Drowned God– the God of Seven is the only one that doesn’t actually, like, do anything. And Bran would know that.)

blog.name: twhiddlegirl
blog.title: - I'm freaky -
blog.description:
“You,” Ned said, kissing her lightly on the brow, “will marry a king and rule his castle, and your sons will be knights and princes and lords and, yes, perhaps even a High Septon.”
"Corn,” the bird said, and, “King," and, “Snow, Jon Snow, Jon Snow.” That was queer. The bird had never said his full name before, as best Jon could recall.
Bring her home, Mance... You owe me this one little girl.
She found herself wishing that Jon was here with her now.
What do you know of my heart, priestess? What do you know of my sister?
Needle was Jon Snow's smile.﻿

body:
Some of my favorite characters from Game of Thrones sitting on the iron throne, Part 1.

All of these are Official GOT HBO stills from Google and public domain except for the one of Viserion, which is by Cameron Cottrill of The LA Times, and the last one, which came from here. Cersei isn’t really one of my favorite characters (though she definitely deserved a better end than she got), but the idea of her as the Night Queen is definitely an intriguing one, so I included her in that form.
